Yes, that's correct. If you're using Testcontainers to set up dependencies for a test collection in xUnit (or any other test framework), you could switch between Docker and Podman by making the API endpoint URI configurable.

You can create a configuration file to define the endpoint URI and read the endpoint from it in your test method and then use that endpoint to create the `DockerClient` instance.
For example in appsettings.json


```
{
 "DockerEndpoint": "unix:///var/run/podman/io.podman"
}
```
then you can use the configuration to create the `DockerClient` instance in your test


```
using Testcontainers.Core;
using Testcontainers.DockerClientEngine;
...
var endpoint = Configuration.GetValue<string>("DockerEndpoint")
var dockerEndpoint = new Uri(endpoint);
using var client = new DockerClientProvider(dockerEndpoint,new DockerClientConfig()).CreateClient();
using (var container = new DockerContainer("alpine",client))
{
 container.Start();
 //Your test code here
}
```
This way, by changing the endpoint URI in the configuration file, you can switch between using Docker and Podman in your tests without having to change any other code.

Please note that you will need to handle the case if the endpoint is not correct and make sure you read the endpoint from correct place in your application and configure the testcontainers to use it correctly.

